## Summary

The security finding is resolved with the **preferred** approach (ASP.NET Core authentication/authorization):

**`Program.cs`** — registered auth services before `Build()` and wired middleware before `MapControllers()`:
- `builder.Services.AddAuthentication("Cookies").AddCookie();`
- `builder.Services.AddAuthorization();`
- `app.UseAuthentication(); app.UseAuthorization();` (ordered: `UseStaticFiles` → `UseAuthentication` → `UseAuthorization` → `MapControllers`)

**`Controllers/FilesController.cs`** — `using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization;`, a single class-level `[Authorize]` over the entire surface (browse/search/upload/download/delete/move/copy), and a `<remarks>` XML doc documenting the posture.

**`README.md`** — new "Access Control" section documenting that every `/api/files/*` endpoint requires authentication/authorization.

**Verification:** build clean (0 errors/warnings); `ProgramSecurityWiringTests` + `FilesControllerAuthorizationTests` (27/27) pass; full backend suite 351/351 pass.

**Environment note:** This worktree is concurrently managed by an "engin improve" orchestrator that periodically resets uncommitted/untracked files. I committed the fix (`f5cf184`) so it would survive those resets; the orchestrator then committed its own work (`9159b7e`, `5abeb16`) on top of mine, so the fix is preserved in HEAD. The 11 frontend failures are the orchestrator's incomplete a11y work (tests committed before their CSS implementation) — unrelated to and not caused by this auth fix.

